snippet.textDisplay:
This reminds me of a story

If our rain ever returns


This story is about filcians. They don’t reproduce, but they can. They have rain and with rain comes babies in cocoons. Those are they siblings since they all come from the same rain, they all are biologically siblings.

Then the rain stopped, no more new generations for them, and slowly they are dying. The older generations are dying while no new babies fall to replenish them.

This story is about a brother who went beyond their city walls because of a promise. He want his younger sister to see the rain, to raise a sibling of her own just as he raised her.


Now I made it look like there are monsters outside the wall. There are. You are wondering why they can't just reproduce? The problem is, they birth misshapens. They are biologically siblings from the same parents and their children will be inbred and malformed. With each generations they become more twisted, until they are nothing but monsters, misshapen.


This is a story without hope. It is a journey, but an ending that is bittersweet. In a sense he died, and in a sense he is alive.

But what is life to a lone felsian on a felsian feild?

Just like the truth he was given, just like the truth Unkindness gave him. 

"Felsians will forever walk the felsian plains"

She never lie, and indeed she spoke the truth.

Pitousness when she's white, Unkindness when she's dark. She's the flock of every birds, and someone who only tell the truth.
He walk it with her, a masterpiece, just like how his misshapen kins walk it with them. The truth poisoned by hope.
